items.content_text: GPS markers show where I took the photos from. Quite a few Candlebarks in and around this paddock, a few very old with lots of nest holes.

items.title: 8 ids
items.content_text: These 7 bird species were in & around this paddock tree over a 20 minute period. Also, 2 Indian Mynas flew off as I approached. The 3rd pic shows another bird I was unable to identify - short tail, chased off by New Hollands immediately on arrival.

items.title: Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa
items.content_text: Locally rare on the plains part of Riddells Creek (common in forested areas nearby). Plains plants are pretty much restricted to Rail Reserve where there is only one population I am aware of.

items.title: Leptorhynchos tenuifolius
items.content_text: Continued moisture seems to allow this species to retain flowers over a very long period, maybe all year.

items.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
items.content_text: Single old female plant surrounded by many young plants, all female. No male in this copse. The 'fruit' pictured are actually galls, probably Cylindrococcus (Hemiptera).

items.title: Allocasuarina verticillata
items.content_text: Male plant. This species is now locally rare owing to habitat destruction. The few remaining plants appear to be restricted to rail reserves (grassy plains woodland). Possibly no longer a viable remnant population?

items.title: Allocasuarina littoralis
items.content_text: Rare monoecious plant. Pic1 shows female (left) & male (bottom right) flowers on same plant. Pic2 = male plant left, monoecious plant right - latter has many female flowers & cones with a few male flowers on branchlet tips (all visible on pic3).

items.title: Delta bicinctus
items.content_text: Orange Potter Wasp (lives near water, required for pot making). Seems to be distinguished from Delta latreillei latreillei by a three striped abdomen (orange-black-orange, only black-orange in latreillei) and different black & orange pattern on thorax.

items.title: Cryptocheilus bicolor
items.content_text: Spider-hunting wasp with prey. Pulled it along ground and down crack in clay pictured in 2nd photo. They are often seen flying/patrolling just above the ground. ID by Ken Walker.

items.title: Tiphiidae spp.
items.content_text: Female is wingless. Adults feed on nectar. Female burrows into the ground, parasitising beetle larvae & mole crickets. They are important pollinators of native plants. Females sometimes mistaken for ants. (adapted from ABC website)

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax, Oxalis spp.
items.content_text: This species is a vagrant, rarely seen in Victoria. Feeding on oxalis (possibly O.perennans) on a weedy/grassy/mown roadside next to a horse paddock. Flew to many oxalis flowers and the occasional Hypochoeris radicata.

items.title: Eurema smilax smilax
items.content_text: Flying around backyard, seen by a few people but didn't land for a photo. Rarely seen in Vic and doesn't breed here.

items.title: Paropsisterna variicollis
items.content_text: Photos taken over 2 years. Assumed they are all the same species - all photos taken within a few metres on the same tree - Eucalyptus aromaphloia.

items.title: Vanessa itea
items.content_text: Three wing positions. Two individuals photographed. Last pic feeding in garden planted Banksia marginata. Camera flash brightens up pics - it looks almost black in some light/angles.

items.title: Convolvulus remotus
items.content_text: About 100m of white flowered plants on roadside only (no plants at all away from roadside), probably a result of the grader. Some were twining through other plants but this one had nothing to climb on. It was GPSed but I uploaded unGPSed pics.

items.title: Coryphistes ruricola
items.content_text: This grasshopper tried hiding in grass but eventually made a purposeful jump to these dead twigs. Maybe should be called Dead Twig Mimicking Grasshopper as this is what it is mimicking in this instance.

items.title: Xanthorhoe vacuaria
items.content_text: This moth lands and then pushes wings up and down a few times before resting. First pic is wings down, 2nd pic is wings up.

items.title: Fabriogenia spp.
items.content_text: Yellow antennae black spider wasp.

items.title: Heteronympha penelope penelope
items.content_text: Probably 3 individuals pictured. Occasional H.penelope among 1000s of common browns. Similar to male common brown (but no male common brown fly this time of year) and slightly smaller than female common brown. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Heteronympha merope merope
items.content_text: Thousands flying now and for the past 2-3 weeks - all females.

items.title: Heteronympha penelope penelope
items.content_text: Thousands of female Common Browns at this time of year and maybe 1 in 100 is H. penelope. Very difficult to find unless looking hard for them. Looks similar to male Common Browns which have all died by now. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Geitoneura acantha
items.content_text: Occasional individuals seen flying among the thousands of Common Browns. Easy to spot as they are much smaller and a lighter brown.

items.title: Delias harpalyce
items.content_text: Lots around forested area over the past couple of weeks. Regularly feeding on garden planted banksias (marginata on this occasion).

items.title: Arthropodium sp. 3 (aff. strictum)
items.content_text: Keys out best as A.sp.3 but some features of fimbriatum too. fimbriatum because of purple anthers and appendages, unbranched stem, leaves not distantly ciliate (it has distant teeth). sp.3 features - erect fruiting pedicels, leaves present at flowering.

items.title: Tisiphone abeona albifascia
items.content_text: Found in a sedge swamp flying around Lepidosperma laterale, feeding on Blackberry. Found after following up an old record designated 'Riddell' by George Lyell in 1920-30s. Not recorded here since. I found them last year but couldn't get photo until now.

items.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
items.content_text: Stayed overnight on the back door fly-wire, sheltering from the storm of that night. Flew about 10am next morning.
